                {
                  "id": "https://colenda.library.upenn.edu/items/ark:/81431/p3fx74f3x/manifest/annotation/p2",
                  "type": "Annotation",
                  "motivation": "commenting",
                  "body": {
                    "type": "TextualBody",
                    "value": "<p rend=\"Page 2, attached\"/>\n            <p>On <date>Sunday</date> next Dr.<add>?</add> at noon, the ceremony of receiving<lb/>\n                the Divine Covenant of <persName>Abraham</persName> will be performed on a young\n                man<lb/> of 19 years. The romance is interesting &amp; as I have heard<lb/> it from\n                his own lips send this version. About 35 years ago<lb/> a great migration of Jews\n                took place from <placeName>Salonica</placeName> to <placeName>Jerusalem</placeName>:\n                a<lb/> party of the pilgrims were captured by the Greeks &amp; carried to\n                        <placeName><sic>Beyrout</sic></placeName><lb/> and sold as slaves — among\n                whom was a woman with a female<lb/> child at her breast: at the age of 14 this child\n                was betrothed to the<lb/> purchaser &amp; in due time bore him a son (the hero of\n                this tale)<lb/> and two daughters still in a convent. The boy was educated in<lb/>\n                the missionary college &amp; appears very talented: speaks several languages<lb/>\n                (English is one) within the last 2 years his parents died &amp; the grandmother<lb/>\n                who ever adhered to her faith has managed to steal him away<lb/> &amp; having with\n                the aid of others instilled into him a knowledge of<lb/> the religion of his\n                ancestors he has resolved on embracing it.</p>\n            <p rend=\"indent(1)\">In <placeName>England</placeName> they declined admitted him or\n                'twas contrary<lb/> to the Charter &amp; meeting <persName>Rabbi Yechida\n                    Cohen</persName> he advised<lb/> them to proceed to the\n                    <placeName>States</placeName> where any &amp; every thing<lb/> can be done. His\n                Grandmother, a male courier &amp; himself wear<lb/> the Persian dress. <persName>Sir\n                    Abraham</persName> is <add>מוהל</add>:</p>\n            <p>There is also here a <add>שליח</add> from <add>שושן</add> who states that<lb/> there\n                are upwards of 24 thousand Jews there &amp; they are now<lb/> suffering from a\n                persecution similar to that of<lb/>\n                <placeName>Damascus</placeName>. I have not seen his paper — he is now sick<lb/> but\n                        <persName>B<add>?</add></persName> has <sic>shewn</sic> me a letter he rec'd\n                from <persName>Revd<lb/> D. Meldola</persName> on his a/c. It is feared he will lay\n                his bones<lb/> here. This is a brief outline but I believe is substan<lb/>tially\n                correct. Excuse writing. <add>אני חולה אבל לא כתבתי זו לאשתי</add></p>\n            <p rend=\"indent(4)\">\n                <persName role=\"author\">A J M<add>?</add></persName>\n            </p>\n        </body>\n    </text>\n</TEI>"
                  },
